I do see the connection you’re making.

The Musashi angle isn’t simply “be unpredictable.” In The Book of Five Rings, unpredictability serves a purpose: don’t become readable by your opponent. If your actions always follow a fixed pattern, someone else can model you.

The fireworks story illustrates something slightly different.

Everyone else ran the same script:

Danger → Run far away.

The older woman didn’t necessarily out-run anyone. She changed the problem she was solving.

She asked, implicitly:

“What is the trajectory, and what is the minimum movement that gets me out of it?”

One step behind the tree was enough because she was responding to the geometry of the situation rather than following the group’s default behavior.

That’s a useful distinction:

* Reaction follows a learned script.
* Response is fitted to the actual situation.

The simplest move that satisfies the constraint is often the best one.

