What’s between hierarchy and anarchy?

I don’t think there’s a single answer, but several useful possibilities.

Network

Not everyone reports upward. Influence flows through relationships.

Market

No central controller, but not chaos either. Coordination emerges through exchange and incentives.

Ecology

Many independent agents constrained by shared resources and feedback loops.

Game

Rules exist, but no one controls the outcome. Strategy matters.

Protocol

There is no ruler, only agreed-upon rules for interaction.

The Internet is a good example. No single computer commands the others, yet communication works because they share protocols.

Self-organization

Order emerges from many local interactions.

Bird flocks, ant colonies, and traffic patterns often exhibit this.

⸻

If I had to place them on a continuum, it might look like this:

Hierarchy
↓
Governance
↓
Protocols
↓
Networks
↓
Markets
↓
Ecologies
↓
Anarchy

But even that is incomplete, because systems often contain several of these simultaneously.

A military unit has hierarchy internally.

Different military branches coordinate through protocols.

Coalition partners negotiate more like a network.

The battlefield itself behaves much more like an ecology.

